The diseases of globalization
Globalization is put to the test like never before.
Its tensions are simmering everywhere.
Most of sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely enough.
Certain regions of the world have gained significant benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
However, some regions have gained little to no benefits, particularly sub-Saharan Africa.
The US government claims that poor countries are responsible for most of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, according to American leaders, is caused by the African government's incompetence.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let's consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced declining living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the worst in international comparisons of government performance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have had better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with high populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow faster than countries with low populations.
(Like all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries near rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to perform better than countries far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries pay little attention to these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries shift the blame to unlucky countries by claiming they are in some way culturally or politically unable to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify the unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than what rich countries, and especially the United States, have to offer.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely, addressing the fundamental needs of the poorest peoples in the world.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence collected will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distance from markets, etc.
An honest assessment would indicate more clearly that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lectures on the poor governance of poor countries, the real solutions require rich countries to offer sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A striking case will illustrate this situation.
Controlling diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing lifesaving medicines and basic preventive services such as mosquito nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least around $40 per person per year.
This amount represents just a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend over $2,000 per person per year on healthcare, but it exceeds the reach of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire annual budget of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins," we should offer prudent diagnoses, like any good doctor would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their economic growth and development.
In regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air connections, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges relate to controlling diseases, soil fertility, and educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems involve water scarcity, gender discrimination or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all consensus of Washington is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the tough task of making sure everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
